<paragraph blockId="13.[264,1323,1351,1537]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
The 
<typeStatus box="[321,371,1351,1377]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">type</typeStatus>
locality is 
<collectingCountry box="[513,588,1351,1377]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, Rio de Janeiro. Having the females of two species both of which run to 
<taxonomicName box="[426,530,1391,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setosa">
<emphasis box="[426,530,1391,1416]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">P. setosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Borgmeier’s (
<number box="[735,796,1391,1417]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1960.0">1960</number>
) key, I borrowed one of Borgmeier’s specimens from the Museu de Zoologia da Universidade de São Paulo. This revealed that Borgmeier overlooked the unique feature of the almost bare, but finely ridged, patches on the frons (Fig. 
<number box="[438,471,1511,1537]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="10.0">10</number>
).
</paragraph>
